passages.name: month
passages.text:
You do odd jobs around the building for her — set traps for vermin, tend the stepped garden.  With the small amount of money that’s left over at the end of the month, you go to the computer-tower.  Zera remains your favorite interpreter, but you also develop an appreciation for Ol's fearless use of unpleasant emotions, and the heavily physical, almost primitive experiences that Lea curates from the computer.  

<<replace "♦">>♦

In bars and cafes, you debate the future of the technos. You scoff behind the back of a boy who drunkenly but sincerely confides that he’ll one day be, he believes, the first technopriest born into the receiver class.  

<<replace "♦">>♦

You become heavy; mornings, you wake up late, your mouth stale and mucid.  When you drink you eat too many fish, and you can feel the fishrot in your gut, the unseen ragged holes in the darkness inside of you. 

<<replace "♦">>♦

Like a veil, a thin mist, a tiredness comes over you, slowly, getting a bit denser every day, a bit murkier every month, a bit heavier every year. 

<<if $partner eq "yes">>And how long has it been since Mara left?  It's hard to remember...<<endif>>

You're in the <<replace "silver city.">>silver city.

You walk the streets, looking for something to anchor you, but it’s all changed.  The names on the signs don’t look the same. 

<<replace "▣">>▣

passages.text:
If you are moved by their story, you can [[stay|Stay]] here and continue their work.  

You may find what they were looking for after all: maybe the fishless have always been real, and in that case, you stand to make the greatest discovery of all time.  If not, your life would count as a vote, recorded by no one, for a more expansive realism.  We cannot stay here with you, but would take some small comfort in your presence as a caretaker. Perhaps when you die another will take your place.

If you [[leave|canyonleave]], of course, we cannot blame you.  
The wind will cover them with dust, and that will be beautiful, too.

But some felt that a part of the truth had been lost. 

<<replace "◉">>◉ 

We shouldn't, they said, scoff at the old ideas. 

If there were people who lived without fish, wouldn’t it be our responsibility to find them?  What if we, too, could wake, mornings, without those urges?

<<replace "◉">>◉

They took up the work of studying the canyonlands.  They built this camp and lived here, devising methods of searching beneath the rock, monitoring every breeze, attempting through psychic projection to reach the subterranean cities which became, to them, realer each day. 

[[◉|dome5]]<<endreplace>><<endreplace>>

passages.name: dome5
passages.text:
I’ll leave it to you to decide whether the evidence they accumulated amounts to anything.

Whatever the case, they slowly gave it up or died off, one by one.

<<replace "◉">>◉ 

He was the last — dutifully filling the log books, sketching out new methods and ideas, shambling around these tents under the growing burden of his isolation.  

And of course, each day, swallowing the fish that were to kill him, hoping, we suppose, that his work would yield a discovery that would undo what was [[already happening]].<<endreplace>>

passages.name: dome3

He was the last of a race of scientists who investigated the old claims of strange sightings and occurrences in the canyonlands.

For a time, reports of white lights rising from fissures in the earth were fashionable.  Otherworldly things were spotted striding across the rocks with unnerving speed and precision, their brittle legs crooked at unnatural angles.  

<<replace "◉">>◉

We admit that, at that time, it seemed a tacit truth that Out There were things beyond our understanding.  Were these incidents proof that deep beneath the canyon bed there lived an unknown species which had evolved entirely without fishstomachs?  Were they attempting contact?  

[[◉|dome4a]]<<endreplace>>

You publish.  You attend conferences. 

You refuse therapy to remediate the curvature in your spine, and speak when you can on behalf of duct workers' rights.  

You wear your spine proudly; it becomes a text to be read as 
a vote for inclusivity, for honesty.

You are a person, as they say, of [[stature|and yet]].

<<replace "◉">>
In late summer, after you help put the younger kids to sleep, 
you sit out in the birch grove to watch for bog fire. 
When it comes, it's an electric blue and it twitches across the water.
<<endreplace>>

<<replace "◉">>
With frogs, you cut off the feet and slice them in half at the middle.  Then with just a little nick you can get a hold on the legskin and pull it off like a stocking.  
The skin goes in one basket, the meat in another.
<<endreplace>>

<<replace "◉">>
The little kids push to get closer.  You've got six skinned frog legs set out on the table, shiny and fresh.  Doc, you say, here, you can do it.  You hand him a jar of salt.  He looks nervous, but pours some out over the legs.  First the toes start to twitch, just a little, and then all the muscles spasm.  One leg jumps up and flops over on the table. The kids holler in fear and pleasure. 
<<endreplace>>

The fish gnaws its tiny way out of your stomach and begins to eat at your liver, 
under the sign of Sagitarius.

passages.text:
<<timedinsert 2s>><<replace "A vibratory hum began to permeate the room.">>Although the pedestal was like a stage, people didn’t necessarily treat it as one — some watched the girl, yes, and others seemed to disregard her entirely.  The focus instead was on this hum that somehow came from her hands and the liver. But you watched her.  You saw the concentration on her face as her searching hands located something inside the organ.  You saw her, after moments of careful deliberation in her movements, make with her hands a violent rending twist — and a white electric fuzz cracked through the room.  Something was torn open that had been before closed, and a spasm of color and noise worked together in a frantic rhythm that pulsed through your nervous system.  The crowd was overcome. People flung themselves against the walls, collapsed to the floor, swallowed fish endlessly; some became spontaneously ill, others seemed to float.   Some changed form to become diamond reptiles or translucent amoebic masses.  The girl on the pedestal changed too, but she left something of her girl-body behind, and the thing that was gained defied description, so it is easier to say that she did not change.  

In the room was a feeling like a storm that could kill time and false consciousness.
